#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"After specifying a neighbourhood boundary, you are in the main editing\n"
"mode. There are four editing controls available, but first you need to\n"
"understand the cells and shortcuts shown on the map."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Understanding the map: cells"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "This example neighbourhood is bounded on all sides by a grey main road,\n"
#~ "where we assume the road is designed to handle a higher volume of traffic.\n"
#~ "The smaller coloured areas inside the neighbourhood are <0>cells</0>, showing internal connectivity for a driver. If a driver enters the\n"
#~ "neighbourhood by the blue arrow, they are only able to reach the area\n"
#~ "shown in blue; they can’t drive to the yellow or pink cells without\n"
#~ "exiting back onto the main road, then re-entering the neighbourhood\n"
#~ "somewhere else."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Another example is shown below. The orange cell is effectively a small\n"
"cul-de-sac; a driver won’t enter unless their journey starts or ends\n"
"there. They can’t access the larger blue cell."
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Aside from these smaller cells, this neighbourhood mainly consists of the\n"
#~ "large blue cell. There are many points where a driver can enter and exit\n"
#~ "this cell. Because the blue cell stretches so far, a driver can enter from\n"
#~ "the south and drive all the way through to the north."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "If understanding the cells as areas is confusing or inconvenient, you can\n"
#~ "modify the map style and colour the roads by their cell instead:"
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Understanding the map: shortcuts"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "To design an effective LTN, you must limit the traffic cutting through the\n"
#~ "neighbourhood. <0>Shortcuts</0> show the possible routes through\n"
#~ "a neighbourhood a driver might take when avoiding main roads. They do not include\n"
#~ "journeys starting or ending somewhere in the neighbourhood, just routes that\n"
#~ "pass through without stopping. These are shown in shades of red; the white\n"
#~ "streets are dead-ends and cul-de-sacs; a driver has no reason to go there unless\n"
#~ "their trip starts or ends there. The darkest reds show the streets most likely\n"
#~ "to see lots of traffic cutting through. The darkest red is along the long north/south\n"
#~ "street:"
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"To understand why, you can use the Shortcuts tool at the top. If we\n"
"inspect this street, we see one example shortcut from north to south:"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "The tool identifies 51 different shortcuts passing through this one\n"
#~ "street, showing the most advantageous shortcuts first – the ones that save\n"
#~ "the driver the most time by cutting through the middle of the\n"
#~ "neighbourhood. Most of the shortcuts are simple variations, changing the\n"
#~ "exact entrance or exit. There are also some shortcuts involving the\n"
#~ "western boundary:"
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "The tool counts these shortcuts in a simple way:"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Find all entrances and exits onto streets from the main roads"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "For every combination, calculate the fastest driving route, using the\n"
#~ "speed limit and length of each road. Main roads are penalised as having\n"
#~ "half their speed limit, to simulate delays in heavy traffic conditions."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Any route that crosses a main road is discarded"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Count the number of routes crossing each street segment"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "The tool assumes a driver is equally likely to enter and exit the\n"
#~ "neighbourhood through any point, but of course this doesn’t reflect the\n"
#~ "real traffic patterns in the larger area. Maybe the northern boundary of\n"
#~ "this neighbourhood isn’t attractive for drivers, because there’s no reason\n"
#~ "to drive that way. (In this case, since the neighbourhood is just north of\n"
#~ "Aberdeen city centre and the north/south shortcut is parallel to an A\n"
#~ "road, it <0>is</0> likely a shortcut that happens in practice.)\n"
#~ "The tool’s assumptions are necessary to make due to a lack of detailed\n"
#~ "traffic pattern data, and because they can be calculated even as you start\n"
#~ "to edit the neighbourhood. The shortcuts simply show what is <1>possible</1> for drivers to do, not what is likely. You may need\n"
#~ "to apply your own local knowledge, judgment, or traffic counters to verify\n"
#~ "a shortcut is actually a problem in practice."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Editing: modal filters"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Now that you understand shortcuts, let’s move on to the interventions you\n"
#~ "can propose to fix these problems. The main tool is the <0>modal filter</0>, or point closure. It stops drivers from passing through a street, while\n"
#~ "still allowing pedestrians and cyclists (and sometimes buses, emergency\n"
#~ "vehicles, etc) through. Let’s try adding a modal filter along the\n"
#~ "north/south shortcut:"
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Immediately after you click to add the filter, you’ll see the red\n"
"shortcuts jump to the right, zig-zagging to avoid the new filter. If you\n"
"add a second filter there, you’ll see a big change:"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "The blue cell has been split into a new yellow cell, making it clear that\n"
#~ "now the north/south shortcut is totally impossible."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"You may have noticed the modal filter icons on the map are different.\n"
"There are four types you can choose from:"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "In the scope of the tool, these all mean the same thing – a driver cannot\n"
#~ "pass through. You can use the different types to communicate more specific\n"
#~ "proposals. School streets are timed closures, but the tool will model the\n"
#~ "effects of the filter during school hours. When you place a filter on a\n"
#~ "street that currently has a bus route along it, you will automatically get\n"
#~ "a bus gate, which uses camera enforcement and doesn’t physically prevent\n"
#~ "vehicles from crossing. The specifics of the physical intervention are\n"
#~ "outside the scope of this tool – depending on width constraints, allowing\n"
#~ "adequate room for bin lorries to turn, and so on, the physical\n"
#~ "implementation of a filter could be a pocket park, removable bollards,\n"
#~ "concrete, etc. The LTN tool’s purpose is to focus on the strategic\n"
#~ "planning."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Editing: diagonal modal filters"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Modal filters usually apply at one point along a street, but when you have\n"
#~ "a four-way intersection, you can click it to toggle through two possible\n"
#~ "diagonal filters. These allow traffic through the intersection only for\n"
#~ "some combinations of streets."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Editing: one-way streets"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "You can also change the direction of traffic flow along a street. This is\n"
#~ "helpful to retain through-traffic in one direction, but funnel it back out\n"
#~ "to a main road. Or sometimes a shortcut is only problematic in one\n"
#~ "direction."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"You cannot create new cells only by introducing one-way streets, but you\n"
"can influence shortcuts."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Editing: turn restrictions"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"You can restrict some turns through an intersection without outright\n"
"preventing all movement. This may be useful to prevent unprotected turns\n"
"to or from a main road when there is no room for a turning lane."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Note that existing turn restrictions are automatically added from\n"
"OpenStreetMap data. There are some complex situations near dual\n"
"carriageways that may not be detected correctly; please contact the team\n"
"to report this problem if you encounter one."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Editing: main road classification"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"When you initially create a neighbourhood from its boundary, some roads\n"
"count as <0>main roads</0>, shown in grey. The initial\n"
"classification is taken from OpenStreetMap data. Main roads are intended\n"
"to handle through-traffic, and so the tool does not calculate shortcuts\n"
"along main roads, and the cells are determined by connections to main\n"
"roads. In the example below, there are main roads surrounding the\n"
"perimeter of the neighbourhood, which is typical, but there are also two\n"
"north/south main roads in the middle, causing there to be cells on each\n"
"side."
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "You may want to reclassify these main roads, and treat them like\n"
#~ "residential streets that should not carry through-traffic. This could make\n"
#~ "sense in the context of a larger circulation plan, a redesign to the\n"
#~ "strategic road network in the wider area, or when the main road is a high\n"
#~ "street with heavy foot and cycling traffic. No matter the reason, you can\n"
#~ "mark new main roads or erase main roads using one of the tools. In complex\n"
#~ "areas, it may be simplest to first <0>Erase all main roads</0> and then <1>Mark as main along a route</1>. After removing those two interior main\n"
#~ "roads, the neighbourhood looks like one big cell:"
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"You can now make other edits and see the effects on cells and shortcuts\n"
"through the entire area."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Exploring effects"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "As you design an LTN, you are already understanding the effects on traffic\n"
#~ "through the area, by paying attention to cells and shortcuts. You can also\n"
#~ "study the effects on the entire study area."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Effect on one journey"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "A common concern during public consultations is that a driving route that\n"
#~ "previously cut through a neighbourhood will become much longer or\n"
#~ "impossible after an LTN is created. You can use the route tool to evaluate\n"
#~ "journeys between a start and end point. The red line shows the fastest\n"
#~ "route before any changes you’ve made, and the blue line shows the new\n"
#~ "route accounting for your new modal filters, one-ways, and turn\n"
#~ "restrictions. When you see just a blue line, it means both routes are the\n"
#~ "same – your changes had no effect on this journey."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "The choice of route and the estimated journey time is based on simple\n"
#~ "assumptions that drivers travel at the full speed limit, with no delays at\n"
#~ "junctions or due to traffic. This is of course unrealistic, but there is\n"
#~ "no openly available traffic data everywhere. Usually the fastest route\n"
#~ "stays on main roads, which have higher speed limits, but during heavy\n"
#~ "traffic, drivers are more likely to divert through a neighbourhood street.\n"
#~ "You can model this situation using the slider to slow-down main road\n"
#~ "traffic."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Effect on routes to one destination"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Another concern during public consultations is the effect on residents\n"
#~ "within an LTN who drive. Previously they may have taken a shortcut through\n"
#~ "the neighbourhood to visit the city centre, but a new filter might make\n"
#~ "their journey slightly more inconvenient. You can use a tool to explore\n"
#~ "the change in journey times starting from everywhere in the neighbourhood\n"
#~ "going to one destination, designated by the orange X. Starting a journey\n"
#~ "from most streets isn’t affected by new filters, but a few streets are\n"
#~ "coloured red."
#~ msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Hovering on one of the streets shows the journey before and after the\n"
#~ "changes. You can click any of these to open in the route tool and explore\n"
#~ "further."
#~ msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid "Impact prediction"
msgstr ""

#~ msgid ""
#~ "Suppose a large volume of traffic previously took a shortcut through a\n"
