#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"The Connected Neighbourhood Tool helps you design a Low-Traffic\n"
"Neighbourhood (LTN). This guide is written specifically for the Scottish\n"
"version of the tool, but most of it applies elsewhere too. In this\n"
"guide, we assume you are already familiar with the concept and purpose\n"
"of LTNs. If you have any trouble using the tool, please email the\n"
"maintainer at <0>dabreegster@gmail.com</0> or <1>create a Github issue</1>."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Design your LTN with modal filters, one-way streets, turn\n"
"restrictions, and sometimes by reclassifying main roads"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Start using the tool by going to <0>https://cnt.scot/</0> and picking your study area on the map or from the list. The study areas\n"
"are defined by Local Authority Districts."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"To design an LTN, you first need to specify its boundary. Unless you’re\n"
"working on a large circulation plan, the neighbourhood boundary will\n"
"probably be a much smaller area than the entire study area shown. You\n"
"can create multiple LTNs in one project, but you only need one to start."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"In some cases, the boundary you want will already be shown on the map as\n"
"a coloured area. These areas are found automatically by dividing\n"
"settlements on the map by severances – main roads, railways, and bodies\n"
"of water."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"The red points snap the boundary to roads. Sometimes near a park or body\n"
"of water without any roads, you may wish to draw the boundary in even\n"
"more detail by turning off snapping. Click any red point to turn it\n"
"blue, which you can drag anywhere you like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"The 1st and 2nd point form long line-like “spurs” away from the area.\n"
"Between red snapped points, the tool is trying to find the shortest\n"
"distance path along roads. Sometimes that path on both sides of a point\n"
"will use exactly the same roads, resulting in this spur. When you see\n"
"this happen, you can keep dragging points around, introducing more\n"
"points, and so on to fix the shape to match whatever you intend."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Population density – generally LTNs have greater benefit in denser\n"
"areas"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Collisions – using <0>stats19 data</0> about prior collisions involving pedestrians and cyclists, it may be\n"
"important to target areas with existing problems"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Points of interest – areas with a mix of residential and commercial\n"
"land use can be important to improve walking and cycling"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"This example neighbourhood is bounded on all sides by a grey main road,\n"
"where we assume the road is designed to handle a higher volume of\n"
"traffic. The smaller coloured areas inside the neighbourhood are <0>cells</0>, showing internal connectivity for a driver. If a driver enters the\n"
"neighbourhood by the blue arrow, they are only able to reach the area\n"
"shown in blue; they can’t drive to the yellow or pink cells without\n"
"exiting back onto the main road, then re-entering the neighbourhood\n"
"somewhere else."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Aside from these smaller cells, this neighbourhood mainly consists of\n"
"the large blue cell. There are many points where a driver can enter and\n"
"exit this cell. Because the blue cell stretches so far, a driver can\n"
"enter from the south and drive all the way through to the north."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"If understanding the cells as areas is confusing or inconvenient, you\n"
"can modify the map style and colour the roads by their cell instead:"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"To design an effective LTN, you must limit the traffic cutting through\n"
"the neighbourhood. <0>Shortcuts</0> show the possible routes through\n"
"a neighbourhood a driver might take when avoiding main roads. They do not\n"
"include journeys starting or ending somewhere in the neighbourhood, just\n"
"routes that pass through without stopping. These are shown in shades of red;\n"
"the white streets are dead-ends and cul-de-sacs; a driver has no reason to\n"
"go there unless their trip starts or ends there. The darkest reds show the\n"
"streets most likely to see lots of traffic cutting through. The darkest red\n"
"is along the long north/south street:"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"The tool identifies 51 different shortcuts passing through this one\n"
"street, showing the most advantageous shortcuts first – the ones that\n"
"save the driver the most time by cutting through the middle of the\n"
"neighbourhood. Most of the shortcuts are simple variations, changing the\n"
"exact entrance or exit. There are also some shortcuts involving the\n"
"western boundary:"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"For every combination, calculate the fastest driving route, using the\n"
"speed limit and length of each road. Main roads are penalised as\n"
"having half their speed limit, to simulate delays in heavy traffic\n"
"conditions."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"The tool assumes a driver is equally likely to enter and exit the\n"
"neighbourhood through any point, but of course this doesn’t reflect the\n"
"real traffic patterns in the larger area. Maybe the northern boundary of\n"
"this neighbourhood isn’t attractive for drivers, because there’s no\n"
"reason to drive that way. (In this case, since the neighbourhood is just\n"
"north of Aberdeen city centre and the north/south shortcut is parallel\n"
"to an A road, it <0>is</0> likely a shortcut that happens in\n"
"practice.) The tool’s assumptions are necessary to make due to a lack of\n"
"detailed traffic pattern data, and because they can be calculated even\n"
"as you start to edit the neighbourhood. The shortcuts simply show what\n"
"is <1>possible</1> for drivers to do, not what is likely. You may\n"
"need to apply your own local knowledge, judgment, or traffic counters to\n"
"verify a shortcut is actually a problem in practice."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Now that you understand shortcuts, let’s move on to the interventions\n"
"you can propose to fix these problems. The main tool is the <0>modal filter</0>, or point closure. It stops drivers from passing through a street,\n"
"while still allowing pedestrians and cyclists (and sometimes buses,\n"
"emergency vehicles, etc) through. Let’s try adding a modal filter along\n"
"the north/south shortcut:"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"The blue cell has been split into a new yellow cell, making it clear\n"
"that now the north/south shortcut is totally impossible."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"In the scope of the tool, these all mean the same thing – a driver\n"
"cannot pass through. You can use the different types to communicate more\n"
"specific proposals. School streets are timed closures, but the tool will\n"
"model the effects of the filter during school hours. When you place a\n"
"filter on a street that currently has a bus route along it, you will\n"
"automatically get a bus gate, which uses camera enforcement and doesn’t\n"
"physically prevent vehicles from crossing. The specifics of the physical\n"
"intervention are outside the scope of this tool – depending on width\n"
"constraints, allowing adequate room for bin lorries to turn, and so on,\n"
"the physical implementation of a filter could be a pocket park,\n"
"removable bollards, concrete, etc. The LTN tool’s purpose is to focus on\n"
"the strategic planning."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Modal filters usually apply at one point along a street, but when you\n"
"have a four-way intersection, you can click it to toggle through two\n"
"possible diagonal filters. These allow traffic through the intersection\n"
"only for some combinations of streets."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"You can also change the direction of traffic flow along a street. This\n"
"is helpful to retain through-traffic in one direction, but funnel it\n"
"back out to a main road. Or sometimes a shortcut is only problematic in\n"
"one direction."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"You may want to reclassify these main roads, and treat them like\n"
"residential streets that should not carry through-traffic. This could\n"
"make sense in the context of a larger circulation plan, a redesign to\n"
"the strategic road network in the wider area, or when the main road is a\n"
"high street with heavy foot and cycling traffic. No matter the reason,\n"
"you can mark new main roads or erase main roads using one of the tools.\n"
"In complex areas, it may be simplest to first <0>Erase all main roads</0> and then <1>Mark as main along a route</1>. After removing those two interior\n"
"main roads, the neighbourhood looks like one big cell:"
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"As you design an LTN, you are already understanding the effects on\n"
"traffic through the area, by paying attention to cells and shortcuts.\n"
"You can also study the effects on the entire study area."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"A common concern during public consultations is that a driving route\n"
"that previously cut through a neighbourhood will become much longer or\n"
"impossible after an LTN is created. You can use the route tool to\n"
"evaluate journeys between a start and end point. The red line shows the\n"
"fastest route before any changes you’ve made, and the blue line shows\n"
"the new route accounting for your new modal filters, one-ways, and turn\n"
"restrictions. When you see just a blue line, it means both routes are\n"
"the same – your changes had no effect on this journey."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"The choice of route and the estimated journey time is based on simple\n"
"assumptions that drivers travel at the full speed limit, with no delays\n"
"at junctions or due to traffic. This is of course unrealistic, but there\n"
"is no openly available traffic data everywhere. Usually the fastest\n"
"route stays on main roads, which have higher speed limits, but during\n"
"heavy traffic, drivers are more likely to divert through a neighbourhood\n"
"street. You can model this situation using the slider to slow-down main\n"
"road traffic."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Another concern during public consultations is the effect on residents\n"
"within an LTN who drive. Previously they may have taken a shortcut\n"
"through the neighbourhood to visit the city centre, but a new filter\n"
"might make their journey slightly more inconvenient. You can use a tool\n"
"to explore the change in journey times starting from everywhere in the\n"
"neighbourhood going to one destination, designated by the orange X.\n"
"Starting a journey from most streets isn’t affected by new filters, but\n"
"a few streets are coloured red."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Hovering on one of the streets shows the journey before and after the\n"
"changes. You can click any of these to open in the route tool and\n"
"explore further."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"Suppose a large volume of traffic previously took a shortcut through a\n"
"neighbourhood. After designing an LTN to address this problem, will\n"
"those drivers stick to main roads, or is there a different detour\n"
"through an adjacent neighbourhood they might try? To understand these\n"
"possible spillover effects, we need to understand the overall patterns\n"
"of traffic in the wider study area. Origin/destination datasets describe\n"
"where journeys begin and end. The LTN tool’s impact prediction mode\n"
"calculates the route each trip would take before and after your edits,\n"
"and then identifies red streets in the entire study area that may\n"
"experience higher traffic and green streets that should experience lower\n"
"traffic. In the example below, there are two LTNs, shown as grey areas,\n"
"each with new modal filters."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
"By default, this tool uses the “Calculate quickly” option, which\n"
"samples only one journey between census zones, and weights the result\n"
"based on the number of trips between the zones. “Calculate more\n"
"accurately” takes longer, but simulates many journeys between zones."
msgstr ""

#: src/user_guide/Page.svelte
msgid ""
